	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-10931" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-10931" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/700a7e365245ddcdabff927eb5420cf3?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name">Adrian</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2011/how-to-cope-with-a-hacked-site/comment-page-1/#comment-10931">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2012-06-11T01:19:07+00:00">June 11, 2012 at 1:19 am</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>One addition regarding FTP – after changing your passwords install secure FTP client (like WinSCP) and use most secure connection. That will prevent you from stealing FTP passwords in case your PC is compromised. </p>
<p>Also I would suggest verifying if your website is not blacklisted for containing malware (for example at <a href="http://unmaskparasites.com" rel="nofollow">http://unmaskparasites.com</a>) and also it is very important to do a security testing at least once (for example at <a href="http://www.webyfly.com" rel="nofollow">http://www.webyfly.com</a>).</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
